1
00:00:00,179 --> 00:00:05,180
So in this video, I wanted to share some cool
strategies I learned involving the Anchored

2
00:00:05,180 --> 00:00:06,359
VWAP.

3
00:00:06,359 --> 00:00:11,410
This indicator measures the volume-weighted
average price (VWAP) but starts the calculation

4
00:00:11,410 --> 00:00:13,769
at any time you choose.

5
00:00:13,769 --> 00:00:20,380
Usually with the default VWAP, it takes the
whole day's trading to figure out the average.

6
00:00:20,380 --> 00:00:25,190
But sometimes you just care about what happened
after a certain point.

7
00:00:25,190 --> 00:00:31,200
Like maybe there was big news at lunchtime
that seemed to shift how prices were trading.

8
00:00:31,200 --> 00:00:36,580
With regular VWAP you can't see how prices
acted just since then.

9
00:00:36,580 --> 00:00:41,750
But with Anchored VWAP, you pick the exact
bar on the chart where you want to start the

10
00:00:41,750 --> 00:00:42,750
calculation.

11
00:00:42,750 --> 00:00:47,380
Then it will draw the VWAP line from that
moment onwards.

12
00:00:47,380 --> 00:00:53,329
This lets you see clearly if buyers or sellers
have been in control since that important

13
00:00:53,329 --> 00:00:54,329
event.

14
00:00:54,329 --> 00:01:00,510
You get the benefits of VWAP but customized
to the period that matters most to you.

15
00:01:00,510 --> 00:01:05,770
It's neat because trading is all about recognizing
when things change.

16
00:01:05,770 --> 00:01:12,400
Anchored VWAP helps uncover shifts that regular
VWAP might miss since it always uses the whole

17
00:01:12,400 --> 00:01:13,729
daily session.

18
00:01:13,729 --> 00:01:19,189
You have more flexibility to analyze shorter
windows and focus on what really moved the

19
00:01:19,189 --> 00:01:22,799
market at that key moment you chose.

20
00:01:22,799 --> 00:01:27,520
The price level represented by the Anchored
VWAP serves as a benchmark.

21
00:01:27,520 --> 00:01:33,060
When big funds and banks make lots of trades,
they can't just dump it all at once or it

22
00:01:33,060 --> 00:01:36,520
would really move the price away from where
they want.

23
00:01:36,520 --> 00:01:40,140
So instead they spread it out slowly over
time.

24
00:01:40,140 --> 00:01:44,710
And how do they know if they're getting a
good deal while doing that?

25
00:01:44,710 --> 00:01:47,159
Well, the VWAP line tells them!

26
00:01:47,159 --> 00:01:49,950
It shows the average price up to that point.

27
00:01:49,950 --> 00:01:56,399
On up days, the big boys buy more when price
dips below the VWAP line.

28
00:01:56,399 --> 00:02:00,689
That way they're scooping it up for a bit
cheaper than average.

29
00:02:00,689 --> 00:02:06,810
And on down days, the opposite - they sell
when the price goes above the line to bank

30
00:02:06,810 --> 00:02:10,180
the profits from higher than average prices.

31
00:02:10,180 --> 00:02:15,970
Either way, it helps those big fishes trade
without rocking the boat too much.

32
00:02:15,970 --> 00:02:22,120
So the anchored line gives us an idea of the
"fair value" range that all the big action

33
00:02:22,120 --> 00:02:24,230
is centered around.

34
00:02:24,230 --> 00:02:30,209
And the anchored version is way better because
I can start it whenever I want, even if it

35
00:02:30,209 --> 00:02:33,030
was days or weeks ago!

36
00:02:33,030 --> 00:02:39,300
And then it will keep updating all the way
to present, so I have a VWAP line I can watch

37
00:02:39,300 --> 00:02:44,000
evolve over the whole time period I care about.

38
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:49,019
Regular VWAP won't do that since it's tied
to just one day.

39
00:02:49,019 --> 00:02:54,730
The anchored one gives you full control to
put the starting point wherever is most useful

40
00:02:54,730 --> 00:02:56,430
for reading the chart.

41
00:02:56,430 --> 00:03:01,879
And that makes it way more helpful if I'm
looking at longer time frames than just today.

42
00:03:01,879 --> 00:03:05,810
And it’s also way better than moving averages.

43
00:03:05,810 --> 00:03:12,400
Starting the VWAP anywhere opens up way more
chances to spot opportunities and trends compared

44
00:03:12,400 --> 00:03:13,590
to a moving average.

45
00:03:13,590 --> 00:03:17,760
So how to trade using Anchored VWAP.

46
00:03:17,760 --> 00:03:21,970
Major turning points or events are perfect
spots to add it.

47
00:03:21,970 --> 00:03:27,363
Those were the times when tons of buyers and
sellers were battling it out - so it's a perfect

48
00:03:27,363 --> 00:03:29,620
average to measure from.

49
00:03:29,620 --> 00:03:34,700
In this example, this huge crash would be
perfect to anchor from.

50
00:03:34,700 --> 00:03:39,430
It's obvious something massive happened there
to cause such move.

51
00:03:39,430 --> 00:03:45,540
That dip is definitely a moment the smart
money was piling in, so anchoring there gives

52
00:03:45,540 --> 00:03:49,150
the real picture of what it's done since.

53
00:03:49,150 --> 00:03:55,280
Clicking right on that candle gives us a clear
line to see what happened after all those

54
00:03:55,280 --> 00:03:57,510
people finished trading.

55
00:03:57,510 --> 00:04:01,599
And now it's clear the buyers have been winning
since then.

56
00:04:01,599 --> 00:04:08,040
Most of the action has been above VWAP line,
so bulls have clearly had the power in pushing

57
00:04:08,040 --> 00:04:11,090
it up from that low average price.

58
00:04:11,090 --> 00:04:17,180
It's like we get to watch exactly who's been
in control stage-by-stage after such an important

59
00:04:17,180 --> 00:04:18,930
turning point.

60
00:04:18,930 --> 00:04:24,810
Scouting for pullbacks to the VWAP line is
one of the easiest ways to hunt momentum moves.

61
00:04:24,810 --> 00:04:30,720
When a market is in a strong up trend, it's
natural for it to have little breathers where

62
00:04:30,720 --> 00:04:35,090
it consolidates or dips a bit before blasting
off again.

63
00:04:35,090 --> 00:04:41,050
And the anchored line gives you a perfect
spot to anticipate that mini dip, knowing

64
00:04:41,050 --> 00:04:44,250
it's still respecting the overall trend.

65
00:04:44,250 --> 00:04:50,479
As long as the highs keep getting higher and
price is staying consistently over the VWAP,

66
00:04:50,479 --> 00:04:53,699
you know the buyers are still in control.

67
00:04:53,699 --> 00:04:59,660
All you gotta do is watch for price to touch
back down to the VWAP after stretching out

68
00:04:59,660 --> 00:05:00,950
above it.

69
00:05:00,950 --> 00:05:05,740
That's your low-risk entry to hop on for the
next leg up!

70
00:05:05,740 --> 00:05:11,310
The anchored line basically shows support
developed since that key moment you anchored

71
00:05:11,310 --> 00:05:12,400
it to.

72
00:05:12,400 --> 00:05:17,800
As long as buyers are still strong enough
to keep bounces from falling below, you know

73
00:05:17,800 --> 00:05:20,710
the trend is still in gear.

74
00:05:20,710 --> 00:05:25,169
Looking for euphoric extremes is another way
to use the anchored VWAP.

75
00:05:25,169 --> 00:05:30,400
We've all seen those sky high price runs that
seem unsustainable.

76
00:05:30,400 --> 00:05:35,050
When the price gets waaay over the line, buying
seems risky.

77
00:05:35,050 --> 00:05:41,900
In this example, price hitting the third VWAP
band is a clear signal it's running too hot.

78
00:05:41,900 --> 00:05:47,770
In this case, you must avoid jumping in because
the odds of a pullback are very high.

79
00:05:47,770 --> 00:05:54,280
And for contrarian swing traders and risk
takers, it sets up a sweet chance at a mean

80
00:05:54,280 --> 00:05:56,180
reversion trade!

81
00:05:56,180 --> 00:06:02,180
If you believe in technical analysis and that
everything fluctuates around an average, well

82
00:06:02,180 --> 00:06:09,039
once price moves that far above the VWAP,
the math says it's "due" to a big pullback.

83
00:06:09,039 --> 00:06:14,500
Betting on it coming back to more reasonable
levels starts to make sense the more stretched

84
00:06:14,500 --> 00:06:16,580
out it gets.

85
00:06:16,580 --> 00:06:20,360
Obviously it takes some guts to fade that
kind of momentum.

86
00:06:20,360 --> 00:06:26,180
But scoping for extreme spreads between price
and the anchored line is a good way to trade

87
00:06:26,180 --> 00:06:29,509
some high probability reversal setups.

88
00:06:29,509 --> 00:06:35,620
Patience is key though - no way I'd jump in
to sell right at the top of that euphoria!

89
00:06:35,620 --> 00:06:40,830
But having the anchored lines as guides, you
can spot when something is overbought and

90
00:06:40,830 --> 00:06:43,139
due for a breather.

91
00:06:43,139 --> 00:06:49,520
The Anchored VWAP line can also be used to
confirm trends and identify hidden areas of

92
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:51,970
supply or demand on the chart.

93
00:06:51,970 --> 00:06:57,060
The big thing is we can set it anywhere that
marks an important switch.

94
00:06:57,060 --> 00:07:02,900
Before that point the trading might not tell
us much since sentiment was different.

95
00:07:02,900 --> 00:07:08,849
But once we select our "anchor" bar, that
VWAP line will show us the true average price

96
00:07:08,849 --> 00:07:14,759
based on the price action that happened after
whatever event we chose.

97
00:07:14,759 --> 00:07:21,710
From there it gets real simple - if the market
stays mostly over the line like we see here,

98
00:07:21,710 --> 00:07:25,979
we know buyers are in control of setting the
market value.

99
00:07:25,979 --> 00:07:31,639
And if it respects the line as support on
dips, that's an even stronger sign buyers

100
00:07:31,639 --> 00:07:35,169
are willing to hop in at "fair" prices.

101
00:07:35,169 --> 00:07:40,389
Conversely, prolonged breaks below could mean
sellers have power now.

102
00:07:40,389 --> 00:07:47,419
Remember: the key is choosing the right starting
point to reflect an actual shift in how traders

103
00:07:47,419 --> 00:07:49,000
are thinking.

104
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:54,539
When anchored to the right moment, the line
then becomes your guide for seeing hidden

105
00:07:54,539 --> 00:08:00,780
levels where buying or selling finds support
or turns the price around.

106
00:08:00,780 --> 00:08:02,229
This indicator is versatile.

107
00:08:02,229 --> 00:08:08,199
I use it mainly for swing trading, but if
you’re day trading or scalping, its power

108
00:08:08,199 --> 00:08:09,840
remains the same.

109
00:08:09,840 --> 00:08:13,900
When you plot the standard VWAP, this line,
you could see why you wouldn't get the full

110
00:08:13,900 --> 00:08:20,639
picture - it drags in all that early choppiness
before the real action kicked in.

111
00:08:20,639 --> 00:08:26,180
But when dropping that anchored line at the
morning low, everything suddenly became way

112
00:08:26,180 --> 00:08:27,660
clearer!

113
00:08:27,660 --> 00:08:31,930
That dip was obviously a turning point where
buyers stepped up.

114
00:08:31,930 --> 00:08:38,669
So zeroing in on just the data since then,
the VWAP line perfectly mirrors how the price

115
00:08:38,669 --> 00:08:42,370
has reacted going into the rest of the session.

116
00:08:42,370 --> 00:08:48,320
If my plan was buying a dip at the average
price line, I'd be way better off following

117
00:08:48,320 --> 00:08:49,620
the anchored one.

118
00:08:49,620 --> 00:08:52,899
I can totally see several buy zones with it.

119
00:08:52,899 --> 00:08:56,070
The normal VWAP just doesn't have that precision.

120
00:08:56,070 --> 00:09:02,040
I hope you see how well the anchored line
fits the price action vs the default line.

121
00:09:02,040 --> 00:09:06,100
So, what are the best places to anchor the
line.

122
00:09:06,100 --> 00:09:10,760
Like I said, choosing that starting anchor
point is crucial.

123
00:09:10,760 --> 00:09:16,360
It's gotta line up with a real shift in how
most traders are viewing things, not just

124
00:09:16,360 --> 00:09:19,450
some random spot in the middle of the chart.

125
00:09:19,450 --> 00:09:26,320
Everyone seeing the same key moment is what'll
make that line a meaningful support or resistance.

126
00:09:26,320 --> 00:09:31,780
Think about it, if many are paying attention
to the same place on the chart, there's bound

127
00:09:31,780 --> 00:09:36,220
to be a crowd reaction when price gets back
to that level.

128
00:09:36,220 --> 00:09:40,360
Much more so than an arbitrarily dropped line
or a common moving average.

129
00:09:40,360 --> 00:09:46,380
So make sure the anchor it's at obvious turning
point that others will recognize too.

130
00:09:46,380 --> 00:09:51,260
The line has to start where the whole market's
psychology changed.

131
00:09:51,260 --> 00:09:55,839
I like to monitor volume to find the anchor
point.

132
00:09:55,839 --> 00:10:02,079
That metric reveals so much about what the
big players are really doing under the surface.

133
00:10:02,079 --> 00:10:09,380
A high volume candle shows there's legit interest
building, whether it's bulls or bears in control.

134
00:10:09,380 --> 00:10:15,100
Combining volume spikes with a price pump
is the decent confirmation a new trend might

135
00:10:15,100 --> 00:10:17,269
be kicking off.

136
00:10:17,269 --> 00:10:21,150
Anchoring the VWAP there capitalizes on that
shift.

137
00:10:21,150 --> 00:10:27,070
The line immediately highlighted several clean
dips you could have hopped in for a quick

138
00:10:27,070 --> 00:10:28,820
scalp upwards.

139
00:10:28,820 --> 00:10:32,150
Chasing volume surges is a sweet day trading
approach.

140
00:10:32,150 --> 00:10:39,899
Let the big money lead the way to find legit
breakouts, then play the anchored VWAP bounces

141
00:10:39,899 --> 00:10:44,290
for short rides back up as it regains steam.

142
00:10:44,290 --> 00:10:50,029
Way better than random guesses about support
- this lets the market tell you exactly where

143
00:10:50,029 --> 00:10:51,880
it's at.

144
00:10:51,880 --> 00:10:57,980
Using the anchored VWAP at major swings to
find reversal and bounce plays is another

145
00:10:57,980 --> 00:10:59,040
strategy.

146
00:10:59,040 --> 00:11:03,940
More specifically, I prefer to look for the
first pullback to the line.

147
00:11:03,940 --> 00:11:07,390
That has the greatest potential for a VWAP
bounce.

148
00:11:07,390 --> 00:11:13,350
Just looking for highs and lows is one thing,
but layering in the average price context

149
00:11:13,350 --> 00:11:14,830
blows it wide open.

150
00:11:14,830 --> 00:11:21,670
Plotting them at clear swing highs and lows
really brings hidden levels to light.

151
00:11:21,670 --> 00:11:27,910
Just look here: those anchor lines unveil
hidden demand and supply zones that rookie

152
00:11:27,910 --> 00:11:30,430
traders definitely miss.

153
00:11:30,430 --> 00:11:36,950
Especially on that first pullback after plotting
the anchor - textbook short term setup right

154
00:11:36,950 --> 00:11:38,680
back to demand.

155
00:11:38,680 --> 00:11:43,130
And then seeing it work the same way shorting
off at supply.

156
00:11:43,130 --> 00:11:48,300
These hidden support/resistance zones are
gold for swing trades.

157
00:11:48,300 --> 00:11:53,700
Scaling it down to intraday swings uncovers
even more entries.

158
00:11:53,700 --> 00:11:59,790
Another pro move is plotting anchored VWAP
at earnings or dividend reports, for stock

159
00:11:59,790 --> 00:12:06,010
trading, or after major releases, like Non-Farm
Payrolls for Forex trading.

160
00:12:06,010 --> 00:12:12,029
Those are perfect inflection points where
the whole outlook could flip, so zeroing in

161
00:12:12,029 --> 00:12:17,470
on the before and after gives you a tailored
view of the sentiment shift.

162
00:12:17,470 --> 00:12:23,089
Those are obviously pivotal moments that can
swing a market either way depending on how

163
00:12:23,089 --> 00:12:24,600
the numbers look.

164
00:12:24,600 --> 00:12:31,010
Here on Nvidia, we anchored the VWAP on the
most 2 recent dividend reports.

165
00:12:31,010 --> 00:12:37,420
Even though price traded above and below the
first line, you could totally see it respecting

166
00:12:37,420 --> 00:12:38,870
that level.

167
00:12:38,870 --> 00:12:46,000
The second anchor kicks off a clear bull phase
as buyers took over above the line.

168
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:50,339
Seeing the reaction so clearly with this tool
is game changing.

169
00:12:50,339 --> 00:12:52,120
It makes swing trading a lot easier.

170
00:12:52,120 --> 00:12:53,790
So start watching those report dates closer.

171
00:12:53,790 --> 00:12:59,980
Another awesome way to use anchored VWAP is
around the daily or weekly ranges.

172
00:12:59,980 --> 00:13:05,500
Placing the anchor at previous highs and lows
from the last weeks will give you several

173
00:13:05,500 --> 00:13:09,010
relevant levels, that aren't always plain
to see.

174
00:13:09,010 --> 00:13:15,160
With these anchors plotted, any retest suddenly
becomes loaded with potential.

175
00:13:15,160 --> 00:13:18,769
Much more so than just watching naked highs
and lows on the chart.

176
00:13:18,769 --> 00:13:25,630
It’s a really smart way to identify premium
opportunities when price is testing those

177
00:13:25,630 --> 00:13:27,550
"value areas".

178
00:13:27,550 --> 00:13:33,350
Having those levels mapped out will help you
recognize congestion areas and will give you

179
00:13:33,350 --> 00:13:39,389
an early heads up on potential reversals or
price continuations.

180
00:13:39,389 --> 00:13:44,870
Whether you end up taking a trade off them
or not, the added context they provide is

181
00:13:44,870 --> 00:13:45,870
invaluable.

182
00:13:45,870 --> 00:13:53,079
I've noticed myself picking up on market structure
and analyzing reactions in a whole new light

183
00:13:53,079 --> 00:13:55,310
since incorporating this approach.

184
00:13:55,310 --> 00:14:00,810
The Anchored VWAP is truly the perfect blend
of all the key factors that drive markets

185
00:14:00,810 --> 00:14:03,980
- price, volume and time.

186
00:14:03,980 --> 00:14:09,380
And the flexibility to drop it anywhere you
see fit opens up so many new ways to analyze

187
00:14:09,380 --> 00:14:09,382
a chart.

